segments.text: ...working, hoping that the battery is still up.
Let's see, and today is the 11th of June, Thursday,
and I have the pleasure of being at Cala Vista and talking to Les Appelt,
one of the most generous, thoughtful Aggies of all time.
Les, why did you attend A&M in the first place?
Why there?
There were probably two reasons.
My brother had attended A&M, a very devoted Aggie.
He was several years ahead of me, and the other was probably largely economic.
It was probably the least costly major college to attend.
My economics in my first two years at A&M were covered by the savings I had,
college for two years, at Hollisville.
Skills I had with a, which was simply a fast-moving A&M machine,
I managed to save the beneficent sum of about six or seven hundred dollars in two years.
Now you entered as a freshman in the fall of, fall of 36.
You had visited the campus a number of times before enrolling.
Several times.
When you went,
to enroll, how did you get there?
On the train, the bus?
No, I left my folks in the back seat.
Yeah, now, what were the, what did you take with you, in terms of clothing and supplies?
You see, at that time, uniforms were, it was so inconsequential that I don't remember what I did.
Describe, if you can, how you were received.
How did you get in a dormitory, get in a unit, get enrolled?
I remember not really too good on that, except that the dormitory,
assignment had been made, and I knew where to go.
By the sophomores, either began giving us instructions on campusology,
that we do anything right.
The fact that I had this job at Vessel Hall caused some confusion among our sophomores.
We were, luckily we were in Hall dormitory which was fortunate for me to just directly cross the street.
It was the reason why the Hall.
Yeah.
The fact that I had to go to Nassau exempted me from marching in with the outfit, which annoyed the sophomores going in.
So, it turned out that about once a month, they would have a special session.
At that time, it would come to known as ass-tears.
My transgressions.
I've been fortunate enough to have a job at Nassau.
I'll show you how far the university progressed.
We were reserved for football.
We had John Kimbrough, Ralph, and all the freshmen that got to know the football players.
I think they stayed in there as my freshman and sophomore year.
It's as simple as you can now have.
Can you describe a typical dormitory room at that time?
How was it furnished?
How big was it?
What did you all have in it?
Typical there was two rooms.
It was just basically a shop.
The floors were plastered and painted.
There was bunk beds.
The size of the room, I'd say, there was room for rainbows.
I'd say we could have two desks.
I'd say the room was about 10, about 12.
So, no rug, no curtains?
Not really.
We brought in anything like that.
We let them do that ourselves.
Usually, we had to, somehow or another, we always had to throw up something.
So, we'd hit the deck in the bed.
It wouldn't be on that cold floor.
Describe the campus physically when you arrived.
What was there?
There was quite a bit of space between the main door and the library.
There was a true library in that main building.
Across the street was now the ladies' dormitory.
The building that was used in the animal husbandry department.
Possibly for study or demonstration.
It had some lots there.
And they stored hay in it.
And they had majors there where they'd feed the animals.
I remember that very, very, very, because shortly after all the freshmen came in, and
I think maybe a day or two before actually school started, they aired all the freshmen
out.
Describe airing out the freshmen.
Airing out the freshmen was just, well, they just literally chased you out of your room.
They'd have you and the sophomores there to keep you from coming back in.
And then all the sophomores, all of the campers started hunting down the freshmen.
And they caught most of them.
Long sessions with them.
Those big open areas on the east side of the campus that now are the golf course and the bonfire area.
What were those used for?
Drill fields.
Were those used for drill fields then?
Well, not so much were used.
The engineers used them.
Engineering.
That area was reserved for military instruction.
How were freshmen treated in general?
The juniors and seniors sought to, the sophomores treated the freshmen with bomb leaves.
Exert a predominant attitude was wiped out.
I don't know of any freshmen that ever went through that area that didn't accept an inferior position.
I think Evol was put inside and negative psychology.
That you can't get over.
How often was a board used?
Not near as often as...
And it was a fair sized piece of wood.
Did you ever get hit by a board when you hadn't done anything?
Oh, absolutely.
Normally, how many licks would there be?
The worst experience I had was the board in my junior year.
There was a tradition that sergeant stripes, golf stripes, whatever.
I was made a tech sergeant, which was five stripes.
And then three days later, I was promoted to master sergeant.
My contention was that the juniors and seniors had, I mean the seniors had, the seniors did this.
The seniors had balls.
Fifth year senior named Kent.
Obvious reason, because I guess he knew I protested him.
Made a fatal error.
Blood came in through his...
How satisfied I was about that whole thing.
And your outfit was E?
It was E, engineers.
Now, I wasn't sure about the mess hall job.
But I registered late.
And they informed me of a new company.
And instead of being Walton Hall, that company was in PG Hall, which is an old wood building adjacent to it.
That was really a, really a heartbreaker for me.
I didn't want to take it out of the company.
But it was just one of those things that happened, and I couldn't do anything about it.
But it turned out that F Company had got some pretty good juniors and seniors.
Unusually good bunches.
We had a strong bunch of sophomores.
And so by the time I was a senior, F Company was back up in...
I had been selected as...
It had been...
It was a high-morality one.
Got a mayoral championship my senior year.
By that time, I was glad that I'd been a year at PG Hall and got an F company.
What did PG stand for?
You're saying the initials, P...
That's good.
That's a good one.
I don't remember.
Okay.
All right.
I haven't heard that.
Did your outfits have nicknames?
E and F?
No.
Not really.
Spider D and things like that?
Yeah.
That's...
All right.
Were they both engineering companies?
Yes.
He was an engineer regiment with six guys.
All right.
Now...
Two battalions, three...
Describe the routine of a typical Monday through Friday day.
Got up at what time?
Did what when?
Take me through the whole day.
Eat.
You had a job and...
They had a special session with me.
All right.
So would you...
You'd get over there early, work.
Yeah.
And you'd go to the dorm before your eight o'clock class?
Yeah.
I'd hit the dorm, decide what you wanted to do, then you had to go from one place to
another to sign up.
And about half the time when you got there, the section that you had chosen to fill in
your schedule was full.
So then you had to revise your schedule, go chasing around until you found the section
wasn't full.
It was in Friday classes, Thursday and Saturday classes that were left and if you didn't get
your schedule just right, you didn't get that in the right place.
If you didn't write and get there in a hurry, you'd end up with a lot of discussion.
By the time my sophomore year was formed, the kids could pre-register.
I'd say it's a damn good thing because with 40,000 students against the 4,000 or 5,000
that we had, our system would have to have disintegrated.
Total confusion.
All right.
In this routine, you go to class.
What did you do if you didn't have a class say at 10 o'clock?
What did you do with that off hour?
Well, because I was a sophomore, you're supposed to come back and be available.
Right.
Then you'd come back.
Then after lunch and when you didn't have classes in the afternoon, what did you do
with your afternoons?
Where would you take that now?
This side of the tracks.
East.
It wasn't about three or four hundred yards from my home.
I drove down to Northgate about a quarter mile to Walter Bryan and worked my way back
along the railroad track.
And then I'd come into the back part of this and go take a nap.
That's another thing that they were probably right about by giving me special attention.
Eating cushions, sitting off taking naps.
Both very, very bad deals.
All right.
The routine of the military drills, when did those occur and where?
We had a military science class.
It was an evening formation.
They had a freshman.
I was a freshman out there.
See, I missed that.
Another sin.
Duly castigated.
And I do, I kind of miss the drill.
I never really did learn to drill well.
The Cadet Inspector is Colonel Adcock, and I was selected to command the regiment.
I wanted consideration.
I figured if I was out in front by myself, nobody would notice that I was out of step.
We had a long way to go.
We had squads and platoons, squad right, squad left, and not the Army Drill.
The Army Drill came in during the time.
I was not the most skilled freshman, but they beat me out of step.
But we suffered through that.
Really, then you ate, you went back to your room, you studied.
If you weren't studying, you'd better be sitting in your desk with a book in front of you.
Now the freshmen are always tired.
They're always sleeping.
And so one of the great sins would be caught up to death with your head down on your arm asleep.
That usually ended up with me.
Let's see, in your outfit, who were some special friends that you made?
Oh, I...
I still...
Any of the ones that you...
Describe some of the, you mentioned some of the athletes.
Who were the notable student, students on the campus then?
Was John Kimbrough a noticeable, did everybody know who he was?
Oh yeah, everybody knew.
